    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# Risk Analysis and Operational Cyclicality: The Petrobras Case (PETR4)",
        "\n"
        "[LINK TO THE PROJECT'S REPOSITORY](https://github.com/alisonclayton/Storytelling-and-Risk-Analysis-and-Cyclicality-PETR4.git)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "QI7eemDy--kr"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## 1. Business Case: The Business Problem"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "wBYjcRPV_btl"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "In capital markets and corporate finance, as well as in M&A structuring, evaluating the result of a single fiscal year is a blatant error that induces cyclical overfitting.\n",
        "\n",
        "This occurs primarily with companies exposed to commodities (such as Petrobras) that suffer exogenous supply and demand shocks."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Iy0RfLgeGvgd"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## 2. Objectiv"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "478toJVdAcF7"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "The objective of this quantitative essay is to analyze the Operating Margin (EBIT Margin) as the sole primary metric of the company between 2019 and 2025, isolating the true \"risk signature\" of the business."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "-pehm61ZGtR4"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## 3. The Fiduciary Rationale of the Selected KPIs"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "uENZ4bhNAzr8"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "To avoid the myopia of absolute profit metrics, I implemented a descriptive statistics engine focused on risk and efficiency:\n",
        "\n",
        "*   *Average Margin ($\\mu$):* Represents the company's baseline efficiency (waterline) by purging short-term noise. It is the anchor for *Valuation* (DCF) projections.\n",
        "*   **Volatility / Standard Deviation ($\\sigma$):** Measures absolute risk—how dispersed the results are relative to the mean. In our analysis, we use the population standard deviation.\n",
        "*   **Coefficient of Variation (CV):** The primary relative risk metric. It is the mathematical result of Volatility divided by the Mean ($\\frac{\\sigma}{\\mu}$). A high CV indicates that the operation is unstable and unpredictable, demanding a higher risk premium (WACC) from shareholders.\n",
        "*   **Stress Tests (Min/Max):** The \"Historical Floor\" (Min) simulates the worst real scenario already faced (mitigated *Tail Risk*), while the \"Ceiling\" (Max) exposes the peak of the cycle, which is rarely sustainable in the long term."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "ZPOtxrygGrMH"
      }
    },
    {
